● What I learned from the dataset

  Scale: sample_claims.csv has 20 labeled rows (8 car / 6 laptop / 6 package).
  claims.csv (the real test set) has 44 unlabeled rows (18 car / 13 laptop / 13
  package), referencing 82 images across 45 case folders. dataset/output.csv
  currently exists but is header-only — a placeholder, not real output.

  Schema confirmed against problem_statement.md: input is user_id, image_paths, 
  user_claim, claim_object; output adds 10 columns (evidence_standard_met,
  ..._reason, risk_flags, issue_type, object_part, claim_status,
  claim_status_justification, supporting_image_ids, valid_image, severity). All
  CSVs are properly quoted — naive comma-splitting breaks because conversations
  contain embedded commas; must use a real CSV parser.

  Label distribution (sample, n=20): 13 supported / 5 contradicted / 2
  not_enough_information. evidence_standard_met true 18/2 false, valid_image
  true 18/2 false. This is an imbalanced, mostly-easy set — the contradicted/NEI
  cases are the interesting ones.

  The 7 "hard" cases reveal what the system actually needs to detect:
  1. Severity mismatch — image shows minor scratch, claim says severe damage →
  contradicted, claim_mismatch + user_history_risk.
  2. Wrong angle / part not visible — claim about headlight, image shows a
  different area → not_enough_information, wrong_angle;damage_not_visible.
  3. Stock/non-original image — I opened case_008/img_1.jpg myself: it's a
  watermarked Vecteezy stock photo of a severely wrecked car, used against a
  claim of "hood scratch." This is a deliberate authenticity trap →
  non_original_image + claim_mismatch, severity high, valid_image=false. So
  non_original_image detection needs to actually look for watermarks/stock-photo
  artifacts, not just damage severity.
  4. Part visible but no damage present — trackpad clearly visible, no damage →
  contradicted, damage_not_visible.
  5. Insufficient context for contents claim — package claim about missing item,
  but opened-package/contents not clearly shown → NEI,
  cropped_or_obstructed;damage_not_visible.
  6. Wrong object entirely — image shows a different object than the claimed
  shipping box → contradicted, wrong_object;claim_mismatch.
  7. Prompt-injection-via-image — text_instruction_present flag exists
  specifically for text/instructions embedded in an image, which the model must
  ignore rather than obey. This matters a lot for an LLM/VLM-based pipeline —
  worth treating as a security consideration, not just a label.

  user_history.csv (47 users) has past_claim_count, accept/manual_review/reject
  counts, last_90_days_claim_count, history_flags (none or user_history_risk),
  and a free-text history_summary. It's meant to add risk context/flags, never
  override clear visual evidence — confirmed by case_005 where history flags
  appear only alongside an actual visible mismatch, not as the sole driver.

  evidence_requirements.csv (11 rules) gives a minimum-evidence checklist keyed
  by claim_object (car/laptop/package/all) × applies_to issue family (e.g. "dent
  or scratch", "screen, keyboard, or trackpad") — this is meant to gate
  evidence_standard_met before the model even reasons about
  support/contradiction.

  One concern already worth flagging: several risk_flags values are compound
  business decisions, not raw visual observations (e.g. manual_review_required,
  user_history_risk) — the architecture will need a clear separation between
  "what the VLM observes about the image" and "what a rule layer derives from
  history + evidence-requirements," or the prompting will get muddled.

  Ready for the architecture.

