● Logging is fixed and verified — the previous failure was a
  heredoc/variable-scoping issue, now using a more reliable append pattern. Both
  the missed entry and this turn are recorded.

  Now, back to the architecture review — before I write any more pipeline code,
  I need your decision on two things I flagged:

  1. The contradicted/supporting_image_ids rule conflicts with your own ground 
  truth. Your Stage 3 spec says: "If claim_status='contradicted' → 
  supporting_image_ids must be 'none'." But every single contradicted row in
  sample_claims.csv has a populated supporting_image_ids (e.g. case_008:
  contradicted, supporting_image_ids=img_1 — the image is what proves the
  contradiction). Implementing the rule as written would actively corrupt
  correct model output to match a pattern that doesn't exist in your own
  benchmark. I'd drop this rule entirely and let supporting_image_ids mean "the
  image(s) the decision is grounded in," regardless of status — only forcing
  none when valid_image=false or no image was usable.

  2. Stage 1's all-images-invalid fallback row is underspecified. You gave
  valid_image=false, evidence_standard_met=false, 
  claim_status=not_enough_information, severity=unknown, risk_flags=none but
  didn't say what issue_type, object_part, supporting_image_ids, and the two
  justification strings should be. I defaulted them in schemas.py
  (DEFAULT_NOT_ENOUGH_INFO) to unknown / unknown / none / generic sentences —
  confirm that's fine or tell me what you want instead.

