● code/pipeline.py is done. It owns:

  - Stage 1: load_user_history/load_evidence_requirements (pandas, loaded once),
  and per-claim load_claim_images. If zero valid images, short-circuits to the
  DEFAULT_NOT_ENOUGH_INFO fallback row we agreed on.
  - Stage 2: fills prompts.CLAIM_ANALYSIS_PROMPT_TEMPLATE with the claim,
  filtered evidence requirements, user-history context (absent users default to
  "new user, no risk" via NO_HISTORY_SUMMARY_TEXT), and the allowed-value lists
  — then calls call_vlm inside the shared asyncio.Semaphore(5).
  - Stage 3: hands off to apply_post_hoc (passing the semaphore through, since
  the enum-fix retry in Stage 3a makes its own bounded VLM call after the Stage
  2 slot is released).
  - run_pipeline() creates one semaphore and asyncio.gather()s all claims.

  Note: pipeline.py imports apply_post_hoc from post_hoc.py, which doesn't exist
  yet — this module won't run until that's written. That's the natural next
