● The run succeeded on all 20 sample claims. A few things worth knowing:

  Setup fixes along the way:
  - Your echo command had no > redirect, so the key only printed to stdout — I
  wrote .env myself from what was already visible in the transcript. Worth
  rotating that key later since it briefly sat in plaintext in this session.
  - No .gitignore existed at all — created one (.env, __pycache__/, *.pyc) so
  the key can never get committed by accident.
  - Hit a real bug on the first run: the API rejected an image with "declared 
  image/jpeg but appears to be image/webp" — at least one .jpg file in the
  dataset is actually WebP content. Fixed image_utils.py to sniff the real
  format from file magic bytes instead of trusting the extension.

  Results (20 claims, ~31s, 20 calls, $0.21):

  ┌────────────────────────┬───────────┬────────┬──────┐
  │         label          │ precision │ recall │  f1  │
  ├────────────────────────┼───────────┼────────┼──────┤
  │ contradicted           │ 1.00      │ 0.40   │ 0.57 │
  ├────────────────────────┼───────────┼────────┼──────┤
  │ not_enough_information │ 0.29      │ 1.00   │ 0.44 │
  ├────────────────────────┼───────────┼────────┼──────┤
  │ supported              │ 0.91      │ 0.77   │ 0.83 │
  └────────────────────────┴───────────┴────────┴──────┘

  Macro F1: 0.62. object_part 90%, supporting_image_ids 75%, claim_status 70%
  accuracy. risk_flags only 15% — multi-label exact-match is strict, worth a
  closer look. evidence_standard_met_reason/claim_status_justification show 0% —
  that's a metrics artifact (free text scored by exact string match will
  essentially never hit), not a real model failure.

  The model is over-predicting not_enough_information (high recall, low
  precision) and under-predicting contradicted (low recall) — likely
  conservative behavior worth tuning if you want to improve the benchmark. Want
  me to dig into the risk_flags mismatches or the
  contradicted/not_enough_information confusion next?

